1 NOTE An item in the original record book of the Ev. Lutheran Immanuel Church, Meriden, CT., indicates she might have been born in Schwarzenau, West Prussia, Germany. Schwarzenau is now Czerniejewo, Poland.
2 CONC  <p></p> <p>When she married Christian Schlack/Schlank, she was listed as unmarried, the daughter of a farm worker and permission to marry was given by her brothers. <p></p> <p>At the time of her marr
2 CONC iage to Gottfried Schwartz, both Carolina and Gottfried were listed as residents of Scharschau, West Prussia, Germany. <p></p> <p>She was a widow when she married Gottfried Schwartz and the boy listed
2 CONC  as their first son, Hermon, was probably her son by her marriage toSchlack/Schlank but was raised by and took Gottfried's name. Sometimes he was known as Hermon Schlack Schwartz. <p></p> <p>She arriv
2 CONC ed on April 28, 1873 in New York aboard the S.S. Wisconsin which sailed from Liverpool and Queenstown with Gottfried Schwartz, Hermon, and twins, Caroline and Wilhelmine Schwartz.
