1 NOTE <p>Nissim ben Jacob ben Nissim ibn Sh─üh─½n was one of the foremost Jewish scholars of the eleventh century and the leader of the North African Jewish community. He was born in 990 in Qayrawan, where 
2 CONC he spent most of his life. His family name (Sh─üh─½n) indicates Persian origins. His father, Jacob, was head of the local academy (Heb. bet midrash) and in 987 wrote to Sherira Gaon in Babylonia in th
2 CONC e name of &ldquo;the holy congregation of Qayrawan,&rdquo; asking him how the Mishna was written. The famous response is known as the Epistle (Heb. Iggeret) of Sherira Gaon. In it Sherira refers to Ja
2 CONC cob as mari (my teacher) and rabbana (our mentor).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>By the end of the tenth century, the academy in Qayrawan had become the most important scholarly institution of North African Je
2 CONC wry. Nissim studied with his father, Jacob, then with Rav ßĖżushiel, who became head of the academy when Jacob passed away in 1006, and with ßĖżushiel&rsquo;s son ßĖżananel. Even at a relatively early
2 CONC  age Nissim was called gaon in recognition of his outstanding scholarship and leadership. After ßĖżushiel&rsquo;s death, even though he was younger than ßĖżananel, Nissim became head of the academy, a
2 CONC  post for which he had been groomed since childhood by his father and the senior members of the Qayrawan community. Following the destruction of Qayrawan in 1057, Rav Nissim lived in several coastal t
2 CONC owns, including Sousse and al-Mahdiya (Almeria), where he died in 1062. His death was mourned by Jews throughout the Maghreb.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Nissim ibn Sh─üh─½n, known by the honorific &ldquo;Re
2 CONC newer of the Faith,&rdquo; was a great scholar, well versed in the religious and philosophical literature of the time, as well as in Muslim religious literature. He corresponded with Hay Gaon in Babyl
2 CONC on and with Samuel ha-Nagid in Spain, and was considered a halakhic authority of the same stature as the Babylonian geonim. His authority enabled the transplantation of Babylonian legal traditions in 
2 CONC the West. He visited Spain often, taught at the Granada academy, and married his daughter to Jehoseph ibn Naghrella. Nissim was also a poet; in fact, according to Samuel ha-Nagid, Ibn Sh─üh─½n&rsquo;s
2 CONC  poems were superior to his own. Isaac al-F─üs─½ studied with him, but never mentioned him as a mentor and often disagreed with him. Nissim visited Granada and taught there. Of importance during his t
2 CONC ime was the disturbed political situation in North Africa, since the local Z─½rid dynasty there was in conflict with the F─üß╣Łimids, and when the Bedouin of the Ban┼½ Hil─ül [q.v.] and the Sulaym att
2 CONC acked Ifr─½ßĖ│iya, and the Z─½rid ruler had to leave al-ßĖ▓ayraw─ün in 449/1057 and take refuge in al-Mahdiyya, Rabbi Niss─½m fled to S┼½sa [q.v.], where he died in 454/1062 after a serious illness.</
2 CONC p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Nissim&rsquo;s commentary on the Talmud was the first systematic work on the Talmud. Written mostly in Hebrew, it fully paraphrased the talmudic text so as to enable detailed study
2 CONC  without any need to consult the text directly. This approach differed substantially from the one favored in Ashkenaz. Nissim&rsquo;s commentary apparently antedated ßĖżananel&rsquo;s. Since the latte
2 CONC r gives a more literal paraphrase, it eventually supplanted Nissim&rsquo;s commentary, which was rarely quoted by later scholars and was mostly lost. Both works were meant to make it possible for stud
2 CONC ents to learn independently without dependence on external sources. Rav Nissim held that the editing of the Talmud was a one-time act, whereas in Sherira&rsquo;s view, as presented in the Epistle, the
2 CONC  redaction of the Talmud was a continuous process.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>In the Kit─üb Mift─üßĖź Maghal─½q al-Talm┼½dh (Ar. Key to the Locks of the Talmud), a prototype of the Massoret ha-Shas genre, N
2 CONC issim provided a further aid to Talmud study. This work, a reference tool, organized tractate by tractate in the standard sequence, enabled access to all the sources mentioned in the Talmud and taught
2 CONC  that a full understanding of any specific talmudic matter requires familiarity with parallel matters in other parts of the Talmud or in other sources. The work also treats aggada, principles of faith
2 CONC , and interfaith discussions, occasionally mentions Sherira and Hay Gaon, the She╩Šiltot and Halakhot Gedolot, and once even ßĖżushiel, and uses both the Palestinian Talmud and the Tosefta. The goal o
2 CONC f this work, as Nissim explains in a long introduction, was to strengthen Jewish faith and explicate the holiness of the Torah. A Hebrew translation of tractates Berakhot, Shabbat, and ╩┐Eruvin has co
2 CONC me down to us, and Arabic segments of tractate Shabbat were found in the Geniza (see Cairo Geniza). The book was often quoted by scholars who were well versed in Arabic.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Megillat 
2 CONC Setarim (Heb. Scroll of Secrets), Nissim&rsquo;s most famous book, consists of 250 items on questions pertaining to halakha, aggada, Bible, and Talmud, religious customs, religious opinions, and issue
2 CONC s of faith. Its title derives from the circumstance that many of the matters it explicates had been unclear until it appeared. The phrase Megillat Setarim first appears in Rav Nissim&rsquo;s commentar
2 CONC y on Tractate Shabbat, but there it refers to a private notebook not meant for publication. This work circulated throughout the Jewish world and until the fourteenth century was used by all the major 
2 CONC scholars both east and west, including France and Ashkenaz. It was written mostly in Hebrew, which facilitated its wide circulation. Nowadays, only some collected selections are left. The book&rsquo;s
2 CONC  original content was revealed by an early index discovered by Simha Assaf in the Geniza.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Also worthy of mention is Nissim&rsquo;s Kit─üb al-Faraj ba╩┐d al-Shidda wa-╩Šl-Sa╩┐a ba╩
2 CONC ┐d al-ßĖī─½qa (Ar. The Book of Relief after Adversity and Ease after Anguish; known in its Hebrew version as ßĖżibbur Yafe meha-Yeshu╩┐a -- An Elegant Composition about Deliverance). Only in the past 
2 CONC hundred years has it become clear that Nissim Ibn Sh─üh─½n was the author of this book on &ldquo;salvation after distress and comfort after trouble,&rdquo; written in response to a request by his fath
2 CONC er-in-law after his son&rsquo;s death. It consists of sixty stories and tales from talmudic, gaonic, and foreign sources. Some of the adaptations from the Talmud include significant changes indicating
2 CONC  that Rav Nissim used other sources; some of the stories are of unknown origin. The book is based on the Arabic genre of al-faraj ba╩┐d al-shidda, anthologies of stories about rescues from great troub
2 CONC le or severe need. The work was translated into English by Brinner (1977).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Shraga Abramson has established that additional compositions attributed to Rav Nissim are included in Me
2 CONC gillat Setarim. Most of his works were copied in his lifetime. Hence even the ones that did not survive were quoted by authors in Spain, Ashkenaz, Provence, Egypt and Palestine.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>N
