1 NOTE <p>T─ühert─½ Family</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>The T─ühert─½s were a Maghreb─½ merchant family active in the period from 1010 to 1075. Together with the houses of Ibn ╩┐Awkal, al-Tustar─½, and Nahray ben Ni
2 CONC ssim, the T─ühert─½s were, in terms of volume of trade, one of the largest and most powerful mercantile operations of their era. While most business endeavors rarely involved cargoes exceeding the val
2 CONC ue of a few hundred dinars, the T─ühert─½s and their counterparts routinely invested in merchandise worth several thousand dinars or more. They were connected to the other great merchant houses via tr
2 CONC ade, apprenticeship, and marriage; their commercial network also included Muslims. They wielded great power within the Jewish community. In a letter found in the Cairo Geniza from M┼½s─ü ibn al-Majj─ü
2 CONC n─½ to the merchant Joseph ibn ╩┐Awkal in Fustat, M┼½s─ü writes that the T─ühert─½s constitute &ldquo;a united group who speak with a single voice&rdquo; (TS 12.218).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>The origins 
2 CONC of the T─ühert─½s cannot be traced any farther back than their base in Qayrawan, but their surname (nisba) indicates that they originally hailed from Tahert (now Tiaret) in the Central Maghreb (modern
2 CONC  Algeria). The family maintained bases in both Qayrawan and Fustat, and did business principally in the markets there, in Sicily, and in al-Andalus. Despite their involvement in the affairs of the yes
2 CONC hivot in Baghdad, no records have survived linking the T─ühert─½s directly to trade in the east. The main focus of their trade was the triangle connecting Egypt, Sicily, and Ifr─½qiya&mdash;and at tim
2 CONC es al-Andalus.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Like the other traders about whom information has survived in the Geniza, the T─ühert─½s were involved with the organized Jewish communities in Baghdad, Jerusalem, 
2 CONC Fustat, and Qayrawan. At least two hundred items of incoming and outgoing T─ühert─½ correspondence have survived in the Geniza.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>The T─ühert─½s were active as traders over the span
2 CONC  of three generations. The first generation included the patriarch of the family, Barh┼½n (Ibr─üh─½m, Abraham) ibn Ism─ü╩┐─½l al-T─ühirt─½, who was based in Qayrawan but set up a base in Fustat in the
2 CONC  early eleventh century. Barh┼½n had at least four sons and two daughters.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>All four of Barh┼½n&rsquo;s sons helped run the firm&rsquo;s operations during the second generation (10
2 CONC 08&ndash;ca. 1040). In order of birth, they were Ab┼½ Ibr─üh─½m Ism─ü╩┐─½l(Samuel), Ab┼½ FaßĖŹl ß╣ó─ülißĖź (Maß╣ŻliaßĖź, d. after 1060), Ab┼½ Sur┼½r IsßĖź─üq, and Ab┼½ al-Khayr M┼½s─ü (d. 1056). Altho
2 CONC ugh based in Qayrawan, the brothers traveled regularly to Egypt, staying there for long periods, both in Fustat and in the flax-growing regions of the Fayyum, especially Buß╣Ż─½r. Two of the brothers 
2 CONC apprenticed in Fustat with the Tustar─½s of the second generation.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>The second generation was also active in the yeshivot of Baghdad and Jerusalem (dual allegiances were not unusua
2 CONC l during this period). In the 1020s, Ism─ü╩┐─½l ben Barh┼½n al-T─ühert─½ organized an appeal for the Jerusalem yeshiva in Qayrawan at the request of Solomon ben Judah. M┼½s─ü ben Barh┼½n al-T─ühert─½ 
2 CONC was also a loyal supporter of the Jerusalem yeshiva and was granted the title ßĖźaver around 1020; in his later years he settled in Jerusalem, where he died. The T─ühert─½s formed part of a tightly kn
2 CONC it network of traders who transported money and queries to and responsa from the yeshivot in Baghdad. The Berekhiah brothers and the T─ühert─½s collected the Qayrawan Jewish community&rsquo;s donation
2 CONC s to the Baghdad yeshivot and passed them on to Joseph ibn ╩┐Awkal or Ism─ü╩┐─½l ben Barh┼½n al-T─ühert─½ in Fustat, who forwarded them on to Baghdad, in some cases via the Tustar─½s; the responsa rec
2 CONC eived in return were carried back to Qayrawan using the same methods. Al-T─ühert─½ is known to have had gaonic responsa copied in Fustat at least once before conveying them to Qayrawan.</p> <p>&nbsp;<
2 CONC /p> <p>The T─ühert─½ brothers also maintained links with the Zirids of Qayrawan, the dynasty of am─½rs who governed Ifr─½qiya (on behalf of the Fatimids until ca. 1040, thereafter independently until 
2 CONC 1148). One brother, probably M┼½s─ü, was granted a ceremonial robe and mantle by a Zirid princess (al-sayyida al-jal─½la). The brothers&rsquo; high rank in the Jewish community and their connections a
2 CONC t court made them prime targets for ambitious upstarts such as Nathan ben Abraham. After usurping the Jerusalem gaonate from Solomon ben Judah in 1038, Nathan granted the title ßĖźemdat ha-yeshiva to 
2 CONC Ism─ü╩┐─½l ben Barh┼½n al-T─ühert─½, a self-serving move aimed at capitalizing not only on Ism─ü╩┐─½l&rsquo;s standing among the Jews of Qayrawan but also on his status in the eyes of the Zirids.</p><
2 CONC p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Of the daughters of the second generation, one married a certain Nissim ibn IsßĖź─üq and bore Nahray ben Nissim, who first apprenticed with his maternal uncle Barh┼½n al-T─ühert─½ and 
2 CONC then went on to found a great mercantile firm of his own, maintaining partnerships with his T─ühert─½ cousins of the second generation. The other daughter married a brother from the Berekhiah family o
2 CONC f Qayrawan.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>The third generation (ca. 1050&ndash;1075) consisted of nine grandsons who maintained the family bases in Qayrawan and Fustat and at least one granddaughter. Confusing
2 CONC ly for the historian but typically for the society, each of the four eldest was named after his grandfather: Barh┼½n ben Ism─ü╩┐─½l (based partly in Fustat, d. ca. 1060); ElßĖźanan ben Ism─ü╩┐─½l (bas
2 CONC ed in Fustat, d. ca. 1062); Barh┼½n ben ß╣ó─ülißĖź (based in Fustat and the Maghreb); Judah ben ß╣ó─ülißĖź (the least involved in the family business); a granddaughter, Sur┼½ra ibn ß╣ó─ülißĖź; Ab┼½ Is
2 CONC ßĖź─üq Barh┼½n b. IsßĖź─üq (based in al-Mahdiyya, Qayrawan, and Fustat); Ab┼½ ╩Šl-Faraj Nissim ibn IsßĖź─üq (also based in the Maghreb with frequent journeys to Fustat and Sicily); Ab┼½ Sahl ╩┐Aß╣Ł─ü╩
2 CONC Š ibn IsßĖź─üq; Barh┼½n ben M┼½s─ü (based in Alexandria, but also attested in Sicily and Palestine, d. 1062); and Ab┼½ Sa╩┐─½d Y┼½suf ibn M┼½s─ü (based in al-Mahdiyya, but also attested in Alexandria 
2 CONC and B┼½ß╣Ż─½r, d. after 1062). Some cousins of the third generation are attested in Sousse, and at least one each in Mazara in Sicily and Barqa in Tripolitania, all likely for extended stays related t
2 CONC o business. The Jewish community of Qayrawan considered Barh┼½n ben M┼½s─ü the most prominent T─ühert─½ of this generation and an exceptionally pious man.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>The second- and third-ge
2 CONC neration T─ühert─½s traded in indigo, silver (ingots and coins), copper, pearls, ivory, brazilwood, lacquer, spices (pepper and mastic), chemicals (including sal ammoniac) for medical, alchemical, and
2 CONC  metallurgical use, and textiles of all kinds, from simple Egyptian flax to wildly luxurious silks and brocades that only the wealthiest could afford to buy.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Marina Rustow</p> <p>
