1 NOTE Judah ben Joseph of Qayrawan

Judah ben Joseph b. SimßĖźa was perhaps the most important figure in the Jewish community of Qayraw─ün toward the end of the tenth century and the beginning of the elev
2 CONC enth. Known in Arabic as Ab┼½ Zikr─½/Zakar─½y─ü╩Š (the usual kunya for the name Judah), he was one of the wealthiest merchants in Qayraw─ün and was on very good terms with the Zirid sultan of Tunisia,
2 CONC  al-Mu╩┐izz ibn B─üd─½s (r. 1016ŌĆō1062), and especially with the young sultanŌĆÖs influential aunt Umm Mall─ül, who, if indeed ŌĆ£the illustrious mistressŌĆØ (Ar. al-sayyida al-jal─½la) mentioned by 
2 CONC Judah in a letter written toward the end of his life (ca. 1020), sent him as a gift ŌĆ£a dove-colored mule from her [stable] with a [beautiful] saddle . . . and beautiful robes of honorŌĆØ (Ar. baghla
2 CONC  f─ükhit─½ya[?] min [ŌĆ”]h─ü bi-sarj . . . wa-khila╩┐ ßĖźis─ün; trans. per Goitein, pp. 79ŌĆō82). According to Goitein, Judah was administrator of the sultanŌĆÖs economic activities and was uniquely p
2 CONC rivileged with authority to make use of the sultanŌĆÖs ship for his own trading ventures. JudahŌĆÖs governmental influence was apparently long-standing, for he was able to successfully intervene with 
2 CONC Zirid officials on behalf of the Jews ŌĆ£resettledŌĆØ from Fez to Ash─½r (apparently by Bulugg─½n ibn Z─½r─½) around 980.

For his exertions on behalf of the Jewish communities of the Maghreb, as al
2 CONC so for his wealth, generosity, and learning, Judah was immortalized in poetic compositions by Hay Gaon (Fleischer, pp. 473ŌĆō482), Isaac ibn Khalf┼½n (Mirsky, no. 6, and perhaps, according to Fleische
2 CONC r, nos. 37ŌĆō40), and at least one other, anonymous poet (Fleischer, pp. 466ŌĆō467). Judah is also distinguished in the extant sources by the titles rosh sidra/rosh ha-seder , rosh kalla, alluf , and 
2 CONC alluf rav pe╩┐alim, and is mentioned in the responsa of the Pumbedita gaons Sherira and Hay. That he died ca. 1020 is evident from a letter written at that time by the sons of Berechiah, Joseph and Ni
2 CONC ssim (Gil, vol. 2, ┬¦149), in which reference is made to ŌĆ£the death in this year of Ab─½ Zikr─½ Judah, may his rest be in EdenŌĆØ (Jud.-Ar. waf─üt Ab─½ Zikr─½ Yeh┼½d─ü n[┼½ßĖź┼Ź] ╩┐[─ōden] f─½ h─üdh
2 CONC ih─½ ╩Šl-sana). He was survived by several sons, one of whom bore the name D┼½nash, and the others, perhaps, Isaac, Joseph, Abraham, and David (see Fleischer, p. 458). Four of JudahŌĆÖs letters (inclu
2 CONC ding the aforementioned) are extant, for the most recent editions of which see Gil, vol. 2, ┬¦┬¦154ŌĆō157.

Michael G. Wechsler

