3 TEXT &amp;lt;p&amp;gt;The Daily Phoenix&amp;lt;br /&amp;gt;Publication place: Columbia, Richland, South Carolina, USA&amp;lt;br /&amp;gt;Date: Feb 28 1873&amp;lt;br /&amp;gt;Text: "...Stowell, of South Bos
4 CONC ton, and James Sturks, of South Boston. latter died soon afterwards. The loss will be very heavy. ... It is now supposed that he froze to death on his way home. There were no marks upon the body of Wh
4 CONC itley, therefore he did not come to his death by violence. ... Washburne will be the next Republican candidate for the Presidency. [ Cincinnati Commercial. ..."&amp;lt;br /&amp;gt;About this sourceThe
4 CONC  Columbia Phoenix (1865-78) arose out of the charred remains of Columbia, the capital city of South Carolina, in the aftermath of the Civil War to record its losses and bear witness to its gradual rec
4 CONC overy. A triweekly newspaper, the Phoenix first appeared on Tuesday, March 21, 1865, mere weeks after fires had razed a third of the city. It struck a defiant tone, declaring, &ldquo;Our city shall sp
4 CONC ring, from her ashes, and our Phoenix, we hope and trust, shall announce the glorious rising! God save the state!&rdquo; For over ten years, it reflected on the hardships (crop failures, the scarcity 
4 CONC of goods and money) and hopes (the return of businesses and railroads, voting rights for African Americans) of the residents of Columbia and neighboring communities in the Midlands region of South Car
4 CONC olina.Proprietor Julian A. Selby boasted considerable experience in the newspaper business, having formerly owned the Tri-Weekly South Carolinian (also called Tri-weekly Carolinian and South Carolinia
4 CONC n). In establishing the Columbia Phoenix, however, he literally started from scratch. In the weeks immediately following the city&rsquo;s destruction, Selby scoured the state for paper, a press, and p
4 CONC rinting supplies. He and his assistants fashioned for themselves the things they could not find. He also secured the services of renowned Southern literary critic, novelist, and poet William Gilmore S
4 CONC imms as editor. Living conditions in the capital city were so desperate that, early on, the staff offered to accept food staples such as bacon, eggs, rice, and potatoes as payment in lieu of cash subs
4 CONC criptions. The first ten issues contained a detailed history of the burning of Columbia, which was separately published as Sack and Destruction of the City of Columbia, S.C., in October 1865 (itself e
4 CONC dited and republished as A City Laid Waste in 2005). Simms departed after six months, but not before Federal troops had arrested him for criticizing their presence in Columbia. Selby edited and publis
4 CONC hed the Phoenix for much of its existence, ceding editorial control only in its twilight years to Henry S. Farley, publisher of the Columbia-based triweekly paper, the Straight-out Democrat.The Columb
4 CONC ia Phoenix changed names several times in the course of its existence. In April 1865, the newspaper split into the Columbia Phoenix, a daily, and the Columbia Tri-weekly Phoenix, which was published e
4 CONC very Tuesday, Thursday, and Saturday. The daily paper changed its name to Columbia Daily Phoenix in May 1865 and then became the Daily Phoenix in July. In 1866, Selby launched the Columbia Weekly Glea
4 CONC ner, a Home Companion, which appeared every Wednesday. In 1875, the owners of a competing newspaper, the Columbia Daily Register, bought the Daily Phoenix. The Tri-weekly Phoenix likely ceased that sa
4 CONC me year. Only scattered issues exist for the years 1876-78, so it is unclear precisely when and why the Daily Phoenix ceased. The last recorded issue appeared on November 3, 1878&amp;lt;/p&amp;gt;
