Baron Hill Estate near Beaumaris was not yet established in Richard Bulkeley's lifetime. From the English Wikipedia pa
2 CONC ge on Baron Hill:

Baron Hill is an estate in Beaumaris, Anglesey, Wales, named after the hill on which it stands. It was established in 1618, in preparation for Prince Henry of Wales's progress to Ir
2 CONC eland, by Sir Richard Bulkeley as the family seat of the influential Bulkeley family.

During the English Civil War, Richard's successor, Colonel Thomas Bulkeley, is said to have invited King Charles 
2 CONC I to take possession of the house and set up his court there.

In the eighteenth century the house was the seat of Lord Viscount Bulkeley[1], who maintained Jacobite sympathies. The Neo-Palladian styl
2 CONC e is obvious from the curved facade of the building to the terraces, follies and balconies; this was the style adopted during the 1776 reconstruction of the mansion by architect Samuel Wyatt. However,
2 CONC  the mansion was originally built in 1618. There is also an icehouse in the gardens and a lodge house.

