"an Elizabethan mansion, now in ruins, at SJ526799 in Clifton (now a district of Runcorn), Cheshire, England. Built for 
2 CONC Sir John Savage, MP in 1565ŌĆō8, Rocksavage was one of the great Elizabethan houses of the county, a leading example of the Elizabethan prodigy house; in 1674, it was the second largest house in Chesh
2 CONC ire. James I visited in 1617. The house was abandoned when it passed into the Cholmondeley family early in the 18th century,[1] and by 1782 only ruins remained."&amp;lt;br/&amp;gt;

