1 NOTE Family and Education b. c.1637, 1st s. of Samuel Sandys I. m. 7 Feb. 1655, Elizabeth (d. 25 May 1714), da. and h. of Sir John Pettus of Chediston, Suff., 3s. (1 d.v.p.) 4da. suc. fa. 1685.1

Offices H
2 CONC eld

Commr. for assessment, Worcs. Aug. 1660-80, 1689-90, Oxon. 1663-80, Notts. 1677-80; conservator, Bedford level 1663-6; commr. for recusants, Worcs. 1675, capt. of militia horse by 1677-?Mar. 1688
2 CONC , dep. lt. 1680-Mar. 1688, 1690-?d., j.p. ?1685-Mar. 1688, 1689-d.; freeman, Bewdley aft. 1685-Sept. 1688.2

Biography Sandys received wages for his service as MP when he was returned for the family b
2 CONC orough of Droitwich in 1661 on his father moving up to represent the county. In the opening sessions of the Cavalier Parliament there is some possibility of confusion with his father and his cousin Wi
2 CONC lliam. But he was probably inactive for reasons of health. He was definitely appointed to 22 committees, including those in the first session to restore the bishops to the House of Lords, to report on
2 CONC  the shortfall in the revenue, and to consider the bill of pains and penalties. Two private bills concerning his constituency passed through the House in this session, for which he probably received p
2 CONC arliamentary wages. He was on both lists of the court party in 1669-71 among those Members who usually voted for supply. On 29 Mar. 1671 he carried up the bill for taking the accounts of the indigent 
2 CONC officersŌĆÖ fund. His name appeared on the Paston list, but Sir Richard Wiseman noted him as absent from the autumn session of 1675. On reflection Shaftesbury marked him in 1677 a degree less ŌĆśvileŌ
2 CONC ĆÖ than his father, and he was not included in the ŌĆśunanimous clubŌĆÖ of court supporters. In the first Exclusion Parliament he was appointed only to the committee of elections and privileges. Shaft
2 CONC esbury now marked him ŌĆśhonestŌĆÖ, and he probably paired with his father in the division on the exclusion bill. He was appointed to no committees in the second Exclusion Parliament and was given lea
2 CONC ve of absence on 16 Dec. 1680. He made way for his father in 1681, and when he regained his seat, with the Earl of PlymouthŌĆÖs recommendation, in James IIŌĆÖs Parliament, he was listed among the Oppo
2 CONC sition, but again totally inactive.3

Sandys replied to the lord lieutenantŌĆÖs questions on the repeal of the Test and Penal Laws that:

he did not know his own mind, found he changed his opinion on 
2 CONC other occasions, and therefore would not promise, not knowing whether upon hearing the debates in Parliament, he might not be prevailed upon to justify his promises. But at present he was of opinion t
2 CONC hat both the Penal Laws and the Test ought to be taken off, but he believed he should not be a Parliament man, his sore eyes and other infirmities rendering him unfit. Despite this qualified affirmati
2 CONC ve he was removed from local office. He was again returned for Droitwich at the general election of 1689. Presumably he supported the Revolution, but he made no recorded speeches in the Convention, an
2 CONC d did not serve on any committees, nor does his name appear on either division list. He stood for the county in 1690, but mysteriously desisted when his chances seemed excellent, and retired from poli
2 CONC tics. He died on 4 Aug. 1701, aged 64, and was buried at Ombersley. By then the family had gone over to the Whigs. His son, who predeceased him, represented the county from 1695 to 1698, and his grand
2 CONC son sat for Worcester from 1718 until raised to the peerage in 1743.4

