1 NOTE Michael Bright was born November 24, 1732, in Heidelberg township, Lancaster (now Lebanon) County, near Sheridan. His father, Michael Brecht, emigrated from Schriessheim, in the Palatinate, to Pennsyl
2 CONC vania, in 1726, when 20 years old. He learned the trade of saddler and located at Reading about 1755. He carried on this occupation successfully until 1762, when he became an innkeeper and owner of th
2 CONC e Farmers' Inn, on the north-west corner of Fifth and Washington streets, which is still standing, though enlarged and owned by his grandson, Francis Bright. In 1774, he was elected as a county commis
2 CONC sioner and served three years. This position at that time was one of large responsibility. In December of that year, he was appointed one of the '' Committee of Observation'' of the county, whose duti
2 CONC es were to collect funds for the relief of Boston, to watch the disaffected citizens and require them to give up their arms, and in general to provide for the common defense. This committee was also k
2 CONC nown as the "Standing Committee." He was a man of considerable character and acquired a large amount of property. He died at Reading in August, 1814. He was married twice, first to Sarah Stoner, by wh
2 CONC om he had two sons, Michael and Jacob; and next to Catharine Bower (widow of Conrad Bower), by whom he had three sons, David, Peter and John, and a daughter Sarah, married to Leonard Rupert.

Buried i
2 CONC n German Reformed Graveyard on 6th & Washington Streets in Reading, Pennsylvania; however he was moved to Charles Evans Cemetery, Reading, Pennsylvania.

Michael BRIGHT Brecht. Born on 6 MAR 1731/1732
2 CONC  in Berkes Co.,,PA. Michael died in PA in 1814, he was 82.
D.A.R. PATRIOT INDEX
Michael Bright (1732-1814) is listed as a Public Servant during the Revolutionary War. He was commissioned in Berkes Co.
2 CONC , Pennsylvania from 1774-1777 to levy supplies and draft soldiers for the army.
Michael first married Sarah STOVER Stoner.
They had the following children:
 i. Michael (1750-1842)
ii. Jacob. Born on 1
2 CONC 4 Jul 1754.ŃĆĆ
Michael second married Catherine HUBER BOWERS.
They had the following children:
i. John. Born on 27 Jan 1767. John died in his youth.
ii. Sarah.
iii. David. Born on 5 Aug 1771. David di
2 CONC ed in 1846, he was 74.
iv. Peter. Born on 26 Jan 1774.
v. John. Born on 29 Jan 1776.

Birth: Nov. 24, 1732 Death: Aug. 1, 1814 Reading Berks County Pennsylvania, USA. Excerpted from "The Transactions 
2 CONC of the Historical Society of Berks County, 1898-1904." "Just before the outbreak of the Revolution, viz., in 1774. Michael Bright was elected one of the commissioners of Berks county, which office he 
2 CONC held for three years. It was at that time a position of great importance and responsibility. As with the opening of hostilities the Provincial Assembly had ceased to meet, the committee of safety at P
2 CONC hiladelphia had assumed its 'powers and under their authority with representatives from the several counties, the commissioners were empowered not only to levy the quota of troops required for the Con
2 CONC tinental army, but to provide for their support. The records show that repeated levies of taxes were made by the commissioners during the war in order to raise funds to arm and provision the troops wh
2 CONC ich were furnished by the county. It was while acting as commissioner in December, 1774, that Michael Bright was appointed as one of the "Committee of Observation" for the county. The formation of thi
2 CONC s committee was recommended by the Congress of Deputies from the several colonies which met in Philadelphia in September, 1774. Pursuant to such recommendation a call was issued for a meeting of the v
2 CONC oters of the county. It was held at the court house in the town of Reading on December 5, 1774, when fifteen prominent citizens were chosen to act on said committee. Among the associates of Mr. Bright
2 CONC  were Edward Biddle, Esq., Christian Schultze, Balser Geehr, Mark Burd, George Nagle, Sebastian Levan and others. The duties of this committee were to collect funds for the relief of the citizens of B
2 CONC oston, to watch those who were disaffected and require them to give up their arms, and in general to provide for the common defense. Before the close of the war Mr. Bright had acquired considerable re
2 CONC al estate consisting largely of out-lots and small tracts of land near the town. These he farmed up to the time of his death, housing his stock, horses and cattle in the extensive stabling on the rear
2 CONC  of his Callowhill street residence. In 1810 he sold to his son David for the consideration of ┬Ż400, the vacant part of his lot No. 391, lying immediately north of his house. It contained 28 feet in 
2 CONC front on Fifth street by 230 feet in depth. Upon the lot David was then erecting a three-story brick dwelling for himself and family. It is still standing and was occupied by him until his death in 18
2 CONC 46. Michael Bright had four children by his second wife, viz., Sarah, David, Peter and John, the last two dying in the lifetime of their parents. He died at Reading August 1, 1814, his widow surviving
2 CONC  him but a few months. They were both buried in the Reformed graveyard on the northeast corner of Sixth and Washington streets, and their remains were afterwards removed to the Bright lot in the Charl
2 CONC es Evans cemetery where the original tombstones to their memory still stand." Family links: Spouse: Catherine Huber Bright (1732 - 1814) Children: Jacob Brecht (1754 - 1815)* *Calculated relationship 
2 CONC Burial: Charles Evans Cemetery Reading Berks County Pennsylvania, USA Created by: Mary Harrell-Sesniak; Record added: Jul 30, 2009; Find A Grave Memorial# 40075449--
