1 NOTE Family and Education b. c.1633, o.s. of Gerard Skrymsher of Aqualate by 1st w. Catherine, da. of Sir Edwin SandysŌĆĀ of Northbourne, Kent. educ. Trinity, Oxf. 1650; M. Temple 1655. m. (1) 1659, Joyce,
2 CONC  da. of William Aubrey of Grendon Bishop, Herefs., s.p.; (2) 29 Aug. 1686, Susanna Ball, wid. of Worcester, s.p. suc. fa. c.1665.1

Offices Held

Commr. for assessment, Herefs. 1667-9, 1677-9, Staffs.
2 CONC  1673-4, 1679-80; sheriff, Staffs. 1668-9, j.p. 1679-82.

Biography Skrymsher was the last of the senior line of an undistinguished family that had acquired Aqualate under Henry VIII and obtained a gr
2 CONC ant of arms in 1584. His father played no known part in public life, but Skrymsher himself was recommended for the order of the Royal Oak at the Restoration with an estate of ┬Ż1,000 p.a. and describe
2 CONC d as ŌĆśvery civil and honestŌĆÖ. However, he had been named after his maternal grandfather, leader of the Opposition in several early Stuart Parliaments, and probably derived his politics also from t
2 CONC his side of the family. He was returned unopposed as country candidate for Stafford at the general election of 1681, but left no trace on the records of the Oxford Parliament. In 1682 he was called a 
2 CONC dissenter, and he attended the Duke of Monmouth on his northern progress. He is unlikely to have stood in 1685, but was listed among the Opposition. On his death in 1689 Aqualate passed to his niece, 
2 CONC the wife of Charles Baldwyn. His widow married the Hon. John Grey.2

Ref Volumes: 1660-1690 Author: A. M. Mimardi├©re
