https://www.ncpedia.org/biography/hunt-william

William Hunt, minister and religious traveler, was born at Rancocas, N
2 CONC .J., the son of William and Mary Woolman Hunt. After the death of his parents when he was very young he was reared by an aunt in Maryland. As a lad he was accepted by the Friends Meeting that he atten
2 CONC ded regularly in the company of this aunt.

Hunt moved to North Carolina when he was about eighteen, presenting his certificate to the Cane Creek Monthly Meeting of Friends in present Alamance County.
2 CONC  In 1733 he married Sarah Mills at the Cane Creek Meetinghouse and settled near New Garden (Guilford College). When a monthly meeting was established at New Garden in 1754, he and his brother Eleazar 
2 CONC were among the charter members. The same year he was recommended to become a minister.

It was the custom of Friends ministers to make religious visits to other meetings, whether in their immediate vi
2 CONC cinity or in other parts of the colonies or in foreign countries. Often such visits would keep the clergymen away from home and family for years. On 18 Oct. 1770 Hunt, accompanied by his nephew Thomas
2 CONC  Thornbrugh, left New Garden to travel through eastern North Carolina, Virginia, Maryland, Pennsylvania, New York, Rhode Island, and Nantucket, Mass. On 4 May 1771, Hunt and Thornbrugh boarded the shi
2 CONC p Mary and Elizabeth out of Philadelphia for London. They were at sea only twenty-three days, a very short journey for sailing vessels.

In England the two were received at most of the meetings and we
2 CONC re housed in the homes of many illustrious Quakers. Leaving England they went to Scotland, Ireland, Holland, and back to England. Hunt was called an eminent minister and was received as a "worthy zeal
2 CONC ous Friend with a good gift." He became ill with smallpox in August 1772 and died the following month; he was buried in the Friends Burial Ground at Newcastle-on-Tyne.

William Hunt's reputation in No
2 CONC rth Carolina is somewhat overshadowed by that of his son, Nathan, also a minister and a traveler in religious service, but best known as one of the founders of New Garden Boarding School (later Guilfo
2 CONC rd College).



----

Son of William and Mary Woolman Hunt

William was a Quaker minister.  He began his ministry at the age of 20, and his first travels were to Virginia and through out the Carolinas
2 CONC .  In 1761 through 1768 he travelled in the New England states.  In 1771 he visited England, while in England he contracted small pox and died.  He was buried in the Friends burial ground at Newcastle
2 CONC -on-Tyne.  A monument was erected in his memory in the New Garden Friends Burial ground in Guilford County, North Carolina.* Reference: [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/20918383/william-hunt Find 
2 CONC A Grave Memorial] - [https://www.geni.com/projects/SmartCopy/18783 SmartCopy]: ''Nov 30 2021, 21:29:47 UTC''


