4 CONC  Elizabeth, da. of Rhys Wynn of Bodychen, Llandrygarn, Anglesey.1

Offices Held
Capital burgess, Beaumaris 1562.2

Biography
As was stated on his first return to Parliament, Rowland Bulkeley was a son
4 CONC  of Sir Richard Bulkeley, late chamberlain of North Wales, and thus the younger brother of Sir Richard Bulkeley, then deputy constable of Beaumaris castle. A leading burgess of Beaumaris, he became a 
4 CONC member of the privileged, self-perpetuating town council which was named on its charter of incorporation of 1562. It is thus somewhat surprising that, after sitting in the first two Marian Parliaments
4 CONC , he was not to do so again during the all but 40 remaining years of his life. Nothing is known of his role in the Commons save that he was not among those Members of MaryŌĆÖs first Parliament who ŌĆś
4 CONC stood for the true religionŌĆÖ, that is, for Protestantism; after 1558 he may have been debarred by religious conservatism, although he is to be distinguished from his namesake of Longslow, Shropshire
4 CONC , who was listed as a recusant in 1590.3

BulkeleyŌĆÖs life appears to have left little trace save for an unfortunate accident in which he was involved. On 29 Sept. 1564 while practising archery outsi
4 CONC de the town he accidentally killed John Thickness. It was his cousin William Bulkeley II who as borough coroner conducted the post-mortem examination which he reported at Beaumaris castle on 2 Oct., a
4 CONC nd within a month Rowland Bulkeley received a pardon. There is no certain evidence of BulkeleyŌĆÖs death but it is presumably his monument in Beaumaris church which records the death of a Rowland Bulk
4 CONC eley on 20 Aug. 1592. His widow may have married Richard Bulkeley, knight of the shire for Anglesey in the Parliament of 1589.4
