SOURCE: Welsh Biography Online, http:/
2 CONC /wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s1-GRIF-PEN-1300.html

GRIFFITH OF PENRHYN (Caerns.) . The family was perhaps the first in North Wales to emerge as the owners of a modern landed estate. They claimed descent fro
2 CONC m Ednyfed Fychan through his son Tudur . The conventional pedigrees attribute the acquisition of Penrhyn and Cochwillan ( see Williams of Cochwillan ) to the marriage ( c. 1300-1310 ) of Griffith ap H
2 CONC eilyn ap Tudur ab Ednyfed Fychan (d. c. 1340 ) to Eva , daughter and heiress of Griffith ap Tudor ap Madog ap Iarddur ; her possessions are said to have formed part of the estates of Iarddur , suppose
2 CONC d founder of one of the so-called ├ó┬Ć┬śfifteen tribes├ó┬Ć┬Ö, who had received them as part of a grant to him of the commote of Arllechwedd Uchaf by Llywelyn the Great . No record evidence exists of s
2 CONC uch a grant. The surveys of Anglesey and Caernarvon of 1352 prove the existence of Iarddur , but provide no support for the story of the grant by Llywelyn the Great . The pedigrees appear to have over
2 CONC simplified a complicated process and, in particular, they attribute the marriage with Eva to the wrong generation and over-emphasize its importance. ( Dwnn , Visitations , ii, 130-1; Thomas , ├ó┬Ć┬ś G
2 CONC enealogical Account of the Families of Penrhyn and Cochwillan ├ó┬Ć┬Ö in Williams , Observations on the Snowdon Mountains ( 1802 ), 163-7; Rec. Caern. , 13).

The patrimony of Tudur ab Ednyfed Fychan
2 CONC  undoubtedly lay in the Four Cantrefs , and record evidence supports the testimony of the pedigrees that his descendants, in the line whence came the families of Griffith of Penrhyn and Williams of Co
2 CONC chwillan , were settled at Nant , in Englefield , and Llangynhafal , in the vale of Clwyd . So far from being settled at Penrhyn early in the 14th cent. , the ├ó┬Ć┬ś Griffith ├ó┬Ć┬Ö family continued t
2 CONC o live in north-east Wales until the close of the century; but three marriage alliances during the century brought them substantial property in Caernarvonshire and Anglesey .

(1) GWILYM AP GRIFFITH
2 CONC  AP HEILYN (third in descent from Tudur ab Ednyfed ), who d. c. 1370 , m. ( c . 1340 ) Eva , daughter of Griffith ap Tudur ap Madog ap Iarddur . Her father (d. c. 1310 ) and brother Gwilym ap Griffith
2 CONC  of Llaniestyn , in Anglesey (d. c. 1375 ) were landowners of some note in Englefield and in various townships in Anglesey ( Twrgarw , Penw├ģ┬Ęnllys ) and Caernarvonshire ( Bodfeio ). She was probably
2 CONC  one of the co-heirs of her brother in ├ó┬Ć┬ś Gafael Iarddur ├ó┬Ć┬Ö in Bodfeio in 1352 , and it was almost certainly this marriage which brought Cochwillan to her husband's family, together with a sha
2 CONC re of her family's lands in Anglesey . By her brother's will, dated 1375 , her son, Griffith ap Gwilym (d. 1405 ├ó┬Ć┬ö see (2) below) inherited further lands in Anglesey and Caernarvonshire .

(2) G
2 CONC RIFFITH AP GWILYM (d. 1405 ) m. ( c . 1360 ) Generys , daughter and heiress of Madog ap Goronwy Fychan who was third in descent from Ednyfed Fychan through his son, Goronwy , ancestor of the Tudor s (
2 CONC see under Ednyfed Fychan ). She brought to her husband lands at Gwredog in Anglesey , together with her share of the family lands at ├ó┬Ć┬ś Gafael Goronwy ab Ednyfed ,├ó┬Ć┬Ö in the township of Cororio
2 CONC n in Caernarvonshire . ├ó┬Ć┬ś Gafael Goronwy ab Ednyfed ├ó┬Ć┬Ö was the nucleus of the Penrhyn estate and the whole Gafael corresponds roughly to the present Penrhyn demesne , or park. This marriage ma
2 CONC rks the first link between the Griffith family and Penrhyn , but Griffith ap Gwilym lived throughout his life in north-east Wales . With his brother BLEDDYN , he d. in rebellion with Owain Glynd├ģ┬Ąr 
2 CONC before Oct. 1406 , but Bleddyn 's descendants, together with those of Griffith ap Gwilym , through his youngest son, Rhys , continued to be represented in Flintshire and Denbighshire until the 16th ce
2 CONC nt. The personal connection of the family with Anglesey and Caernarvonshire began with the eldest and second sons of Griffith ap Gwilym .

(3) The eldest son of Griffith and Generys , GWILYM AP GRIF
2 CONC FITH (d. 1431 ), m. ( c . 1390 ) his kinswoman, Morfydd , daughter of Goronwy ap Tudur (ob. 1382 ) of Penmynydd (see under Ednyfed Fychan ). Gwilym thereby gained a further share in ├ó┬Ć┬ś Gafael Goro
2 CONC nwy ab Ednyfed ├ó┬Ć┬Ö ( Penrhyn ) as well as lands in Anglesey . In 1389 , Gwilym and his younger brother, ROBIN AP GRIFFITH , were granted by their father his lands in Caernarvonshire and Anglesey an
2 CONC d it was probably this step which led to their firm establishment in the area. Lands in Bodfeio were given to Robin , who was the ancestor of the family of Williams of Cochwillan . Gwilym was the real
2 CONC  founder of the Penrhyn family, but his precise place of residence before 1400 is not known. His wife's dowry had strengthened his hold on ├ó┬Ć┬ś Gafael Goronwy ab Ednyfed ├ó┬Ć┬Ö ( Penrhyn ) but his m
2 CONC ain possessions were in the commotes of Menai and Dindaethwy in Anglesey . His wife's mother ( Myfanwy ) and brother ( Tudur ap Goronwy ) were alive in 1397 and might be expected to have lived at Penm
2 CONC ynydd ; nevertheless, Gwilym ap Griffith is described as ├ó┬Ć┬śof Penmynydd ├ó┬Ć┬Ö in 1400 and 1403 , and his will, dated 1430 , was signed there. From 1391 to 1397 he held various crown offices in An
2 CONC glesey , being sheriff in 1396-7 .

His wife's uncles ( Rhys , Gwilym , and Maredudd ap Tudur ) gave full support to their cousin, Owain Glynd├ģ┬Ąr , and see under Ednyfed Fychan ; Gwilym himself wa
2 CONC s more cautious, but he was forced by family and other circumstances to throw in his lot with the rebels about 1402 . (As has been said, his father and uncle died in Glynd├ģ┬Ąr 's service.) His brothe
2 CONC r, Robin of Cochwillan , was also in rebellion but abandoned Glynd├ģ┬Ąr before 1408 , when he appears as a crown official in Caernarvonshire . Gwilym also made his peace with the king before Nov. 1407
2 CONC  , when he was restored to his forfeited possessions and was granted, in addition, the lands of twenty-seven Anglesey adherents of Glynd├ģ┬Ąr who had probably died in rebellion. By 1410 he had been gr
2 CONC anted the forfeited lands of his wife's uncles, Rhys and Gwilym ap Tudur , both of whom adhered to Glynd├ģ┬Ąr to the last. His will, dated 1430 , also refers to lands which he had obtained from his Tu
2 CONC dor kinsmen; his brother-in-law, Tudur ap Goronwy , appears to have d. c. 1400 and his share of the Tudor possessions undoubtedly came into Gwilym 's hands. In all, Gwilym ap Griffith appears to have 
2 CONC succeeded, through his father's marriage, his own, and the effects of the Glynd├ģ┬Ąr rebellion , in gaining control of most of the patrimony of the Tudors ; not the least important of the probable con
2 CONC sequences was the departure of Owain Tudor to seek his fortunes at the court of Henry V .

The date of death of Gwilym 's first wife is not known. Some time after 1405 he m. Joan , daughter of Sir W
2 CONC illiam Stanley of Hooton, Ches. , thus beginning a long and profitable connexion with the rising star of that family. His son by his first wife inherited only his mother's property at Penmynydd , and 
2 CONC he was the ancestor of the later Theodores of that place (see Tudor family, of Penmynydd ). Gwilym ap Griffith d. in 1431 , leaving his great possessions in Anglesey and Caernarvonshire to his son by 
2 CONC the second marriage. ( Penrhyn manuscripts , passim ; Trans. Angl. Antiq. Soc. , 1951 , 34-72; J. R. Jones , ├ó┬Ć┬ś The development of the Penrhyn estate to 1431 ├ó┬Ć┬Ö, University of Wales M.A. thesi
2 CONC s, unpublished.)

From 1431 to 1531 the son, grandson, and great-grandson of Gwilym ap Griffith (each named Gwilym ) held the estate and added to it. (During the 15th cent. the surname ├ó┬Ć┬ś Griffi
2 CONC th ├ó┬Ć┬Ö became established and ├ó┬Ć┬ś Gwilym ├ó┬Ć┬Ö became ├ó┬Ć┬ś William ├ó┬Ć┬Ö in non- Welsh records.) All three showed outstanding skill in steering a safe and profitable course through the dange
2 CONC rous waters of 15th cent. politics; in particular, they allied themselves with prominent English houses, especially the pliant Stanleys ├ó┬Ć┬ö a process which began with the marriage of Gwilym ap Grif
2 CONC fith to Joan Stanley of Hooton . The son of that marriage, GWILYM FYCHAN ( c. 1420 - 1483 ), was under the tutelage of his Stanley kinsmen until he came of age ( Penrhyn MSS. 17-18 ). In 1440 he recei
2 CONC ved letters of denization, freeing him from the operation of the penal laws passed against Welshmen during the Glynd├ģ┬Ąr revolt , on condition that he did not marry a Welsh -woman or hold office; the
2 CONC  ban on holding office was raised in 1443 on the ground that his mother was a Stanley ( Cal. Pat. Rolls, 1436-41 (416), 1441-6 (164) . He m., before 1447 , Ales , daughter and heiress of Sir Richard D
2 CONC alton of Apthorp, Northants. ; the marriage almost certainly reflects the Stanley connection, for Ales Dalton was grand-daughter by her second marriage of Isabel de Pilkington whose daughter by Thomas
2 CONC  de Lathom , her first husband, brought Lathom and Knowsley to the Stanleys . ( Dwnn , Visitations , ii, 155; Penrhyn MSS. 1-4, 7-9, 13 ; G.E.C. , Complete Peerage , iv, 205 n. c.; D.N.B. , liv., 75.)
2 CONC  He m. (2) Gwenllian , daughter of Iorwerth ap David ; ROBERT , his eldest son by this marriage, was the ancestor of the family of Griffith of Plasnewydd , Anglesey , and Llanfairis-gaer, Caerns. ; ED
2 CONC MUND , the second son, founded the estate of Carreg-lwyd , Anglesey . See Griffith , Pedigrees , 47, 56, 57, and articles Griffith of Carreg-lwyd and Griffith , George , 1601 - 1666 . In 1451 he was m
2 CONC ember of a commission appointed to examine the reasons why the revenues of Merioneth were in arrear ( Cal. Pat. Rolls, 1446-52 , 480) and between 1457 and 1463 he was deputy to various chamberlains of
2 CONC  North Wales ( Davies , Conway and Menai Ferries , 47; P.R.O. Min. Acc., 1154/3, 1180/3 ). He does not appear to have held the office of chamberlain . He was probably the William Griffith who, as ├ó┬Ć
2 CONC ┬ś marshall of the King's Hall ,├ó┬Ć┬Ö received grants from Edward IV in 1462 and 1464 , and he served on a number of North Wales commissions during Edward 's reign ( Cal. Pat. Rolls, 1461-7 (117, 293
2 CONC , 329), 1467-77 (54, 490), 1476-85 (121) ). He was d. by 13 Sept. 1483 ( Penrhyn MSS. 38-9 ). A number of contemporary poets sang his praises ├ó┬Ć┬ö Cynwrig ap Dafydd Goch , Dafydd ab Edmwnd , Guto'r 
2 CONC Glyn , Rhys Goch Eryri , and Robin Ddu ( Mostyn MSS. 148, 493, 495, 498, 542 ; Llanst. MSS. 118, 78 ; Gwaith Dafydd ab Edmwnd (ed. T. Roberts ), 107; Gwaith Guto'r Glyn (ed. J. Ll. Williams and I. Wil
2 CONC liams ), 52, 55; Iolo Goch ac Eraill (ed. H. Lewis , T. Roberts and I. Williams ), 307; H. T. Evans , Wales and the Wars of the Roses , 14).

His son and heir by the first marriage, WILLIAM GRIFFITH
2 CONC  ( c. 1445 - 1505/6 ), is not always easy to distinguish from his father. He m. (1) Joan Troutbeck , widow of Sir William Butler of Bewsey, Ches. ; her mother was Margaret , daughter of Sir Thomas Sta
2 CONC nley ( c. 1406 - 1459 ), first baron Stanley ; William Griffith was therefore nephew by marriage to Thomas , first earl of Derby ( 1435 - 1504 ) ├ó┬Ć┬ö another confirmation of the Stanley connection (
2 CONC  Dwnn , Visitations , ii, 167; Penrhyn MSS. 12 ; D.N.B. , liv., 76; Ormerod , Cheshire , ii, 42). In 1476 he is described as ├ó┬Ć┬śking's servant├ó┬Ć┬Ö and ├ó┬Ć┬ś marshall of the King's Hall ├ó┬Ć┬Ö (a
2 CONC n office held by his father) in a grant to him by Edward IV of an annuity of ├é┬Ż18 5s.; the annuity was renewed by Richard III in March 1484 ( Cal. Pat. Rolls , 1476-85 , 18, 418). At Michaelmas 1483
2 CONC  he was appointed chamberlain of North Wales by Richard III ; the appointment was confirmed by Henry VII within a month of Bosworth ( Davies , Conway and Menai Ferries , 48; Owen , Manuscripts rel. to
2 CONC  Wales in the Brit. Mus. , ii, 147; Cal. Pat. Rolls , 1485-94 , 5). His record suggests that he followed very closely the lead of his kinsman, the time-serving earl of Derby , and a poem by Lewis M├ā┬
2 CONC ┤n proves that immediately before Bosworth he shared with lord Strange , Derby 's heir, his perilous imprisonment at Nottingham as hostage for his father's all-too-uncertain loyalty; presumably, he sh
2 CONC ared, too, the same narrow escape from death on the eve of the battle. Tudur Aled also refers, more obscurely, to this crisis in William Griffith 's career. ( Gairdner , Richard III , ed. 1898 , 227-3
2 CONC 8; Mostyn MSS. 148, 467 ; Gwaith Tudur Aled , ed. T. Gwynn Jones , i, 143.) His influential connections were not confined to the Stanley s .

He appears to have m., as his second wife, Elizabeth Gre
2 CONC y , grand-daughter of Reginald , 3rd baron Grey of Ruthin (the enemy of Owain Glynd├ģ┬Ąr ) and first cousin to John Grey , lord Ferrers of Groby ( 1432 - 1461 ) who was the first husband of Elizabeth 
2 CONC Woodville , later queen of Edward IV . ( D.N.B. , xxiii, 193, 197; Williams , Observations on the Snowdon Mountains , 1802 , 174.) The marriage must have brought him into personal contact with the pow
2 CONC erful Greys and Woodvilles and it would explain the presence of a William Griffith as member of Edward IV 's council on 8 Aug. 1482 . ( Gairdner , op. cit., 338-9.)

Under Henry VII he continued to 
2 CONC hold the chamberlainship of North Wales until 1490 when he was replaced by Sir Richard Pole ( Davies , Conway and Menai Ferries , 48, 68.) He was knighted when Arthur was created prince of Wales in 14
2 CONC 89 and he continued to serve on a number of North Wales commissions. ( Cal. Pat. Rolls, 1485-94 , 86, 354.) He d. 1505/6 . ( Penrhyn MSS. 44-5 .) Among poets who sang to him are Tudur Penllyn , Dafydd
2 CONC  Pennant , Dafydd Llwyd ap Llywelyn , Lewis M├ā┬┤n , and Tudur Aled . ( Mostyn MSS. 148, 467, 504, 532, 535 ; Gwaith Tudur Aled , ed. T. Gwynn Jones , i, 142.)

''''''His son, WILLIAM GRIFFITH ( c. 
2 CONC 1480 - 1531 ), does not appear in office until 1508 when he was described as ├ó┬Ć┬ś King's Servant ├ó┬Ć┬Ö and ├ó┬Ć┬ś squire for the body ,├ó┬Ć┬Ö and appointed chamberlain of North Wales ; he continued
2 CONC  to hold the office until his death, with the exception of a short break in 1509 when he made way for Charles Brandon , later duke of Suffolk . ( Cal. Pat. Rolls , 1494-1509 , 569; Davies , Conway and
2 CONC  Menai Ferries , 57; L. and P. Henry VIII , vol. I, part i, 257, 78, and vol. IV, part i, 1941; D.N.B. , vi, 218.) There is some evidence of personal links between the two men. Both were squires of th
2 CONC e body at the same time, and in 1516 Brandon appointed Griffith as one of his deputy justices of North Wales , describing him in the instrument of appointment as his ├ó┬Ć┬śblood relation.├ó┬Ć┬Ö ( Penr
2 CONC hyn MSS. 48 .) Griffith served under Brandon in the French campaign of 1513 ; he was at the siege of Th├ā┬®rouanne , the battle of the Spurs , and the siege of Tournai in Aug. 1513 , and was knighted 
2 CONC at Tournai 25 Sept. 1513 . ( L. and P. Henry VIII , vol. I, part i, 1176, 1496, part ii, 2301, 2480, 2575.) Poems by Lewis M├ā┬┤n , Huw Llwyd ap Dafydd , Tudur Aled , and Gruffydd ap Tudur ap Hywel re
2 CONC fer to his part in the campaign. ( Mostyn MSS. 148, 233, 520, 523, 537, 585 ; Cardiff MSS. 2, 103 ; Gwaith Tudur Aled , ed. T. Gwynn Jones , i, 146.) He appears also to have maintained close relations
2 CONC hips with Sir Rhys ap Thomas of Dynevor . His first wife was Jane , daughter of Sir Thomas Stradling of S. Donats, Glam. , and his wife, Joan , daughter of Thomas Mathew of Radyr, Glam. Sir Thomas Str
2 CONC adling d., 1480 , and his widow m. shortly after Sir Rhys ap Thomas , as his second wife. Poems to William Griffith by Lewis M├ā┬┤n emphasize the links between him and Sir Rhys , whose son, Griffith a
2 CONC p Rhys (b. c. 1480 ├ó┬Ć┬ö see under Rice ) was a contemporary of William Griffith at Court. A Griffith of Penrhyn (almost certainly William Griffith ) was present at the tournament held by Sir Rhys at
2 CONC  Carew in 1507 (see articles Stradling and Mathew ; Mostyn MSS. 148, 470, 581 ; Cambrian Register , 1795 , 49-144). His second wife was Jane , daughter of John Puleston ├ó┬Ć┬ś Hen ├ó┬Ć┬Ö ( the Old ) o
2 CONC f Bersham ( see article Puleston family ); William , his eldest son by this marriage, founded the family of Griffith of Trefarthen ( Griffith , Pedigrees , 125, 185, and article Griffith , John , 16th
2 CONC  cent. ). Apart from those named, the following poets wrote to him: Mathew Brwmffild , Dafydd Pennant , Ifan Dylyniwr , Dafydd Trefor , Ifan ap Madog , Lewis Daron , and Tudur Aled . ( Mostyn MSS. 148
2 CONC , 529, 532, 556, 559, 562, 566, 569, 572, 575 ; Cynfeirdd Lleyn , ed. Myrddin Fardd , 195; Gwaith Tudur Aled , ed. T. Gwynn Jones , i, 145.) He was one of three squires who were concerned with the Cae
2 CONC rwys eisteddfod in 1523 . ( Ll├ā┬¬n Cymru , ii, 130.)

His eldest son, William , d. young and he was succeeded by his second son, EDWARD GRIFFITH , b. 18 May 1511 ( P.R.O. Min. Acc., 4948 ), he was 
2 CONC a correspondent of Thomas Cromwell , mainly in connection with his feud with Richard Bulkeley of Beaumaris ( see under Bulkeley family ); he paid Cromwell an annuity of ten marks for some years and at
2 CONC tempted, unsuccessfully, to gain possession of the Dominican friary at Bangor after its dissolution. He was probably the Edward Griffith who, as yeoman of the guard , was granted a water-mill in the l
2 CONC ordship of Denbigh in 1537 . He was acting on a number of commissions in North Wales until April of 1539 , but in Oct. of that year he was sent with Sir William Brereton ( D.N.B. Suppt. , i, 264) to I
2 CONC reland ; his command (two grand captains , three petty captains , 250 archers , three priests , and two minstrels ) was equivalent to that of Brereton and he was a member of the Irish privy council . 
2 CONC He d. of ├ó┬Ć┬śthe flux ├ó┬Ć┬Ö at Dublin 11 March 1540 . He m. Jane , daughter of Sir John Puleston of Bersham . ( L. and P. Henry VIII , viii, 122, 644, 925, xii, part i, 539 (14), 655, 1154, xiii, p
2 CONC art i, 384 (91), 1289, xiv, part i, 732, 802, 803, 816, part ii, 40, 616, 759, 782, 1539; xv, 74, 82, 199, 327, 342, 355.) His death precipitated a long dispute between RHYS GRIFFITH his younger broth
2 CONC er, who claimed the estates as heir male, and John Puleston , Edward Griffith 's father-in-law, acting for his daughter and her three children ( Jane , Catherine , and Ellen ). Puleston asked Cromwell
2 CONC  for the wardship of the children, and offered him ├é┬Ż40 for his good offices; Rhys Griffith complained that during his absence in Ireland ├ó┬Ć┬śon the king's service ,├ó┬Ć┬Ö his sister-in-law and he
2 CONC r father had ransacked Penrhyn , leaving ├ó┬Ć┬śnothing but the bare walls.├ó┬Ć┬Ö The lord chancellor and the master of the court of wards made an arbitration in 1542 , but the problems involved were s
2 CONC till unsettled in 1559 . Even after the death of Rhys Griffith in 1580 , Sir Edward Bagnall , who had m. one of Edward Griffith 's daughters, was still pursuing his wife's claims in the court of wards
2 CONC  . ( Penrhyn MSS. 50, 2197 ; N.L.W. Jnl. , iii, 40; Lewis , Early Chancery Procs. , 21, 22, 288, 290; Lewis and Davies , Augmentation Recs. , 51; L. and P. Henry VIII , v, no. 724 (10), xv, 433, 661, 
2 CONC xvii, 466, xix 812 (16), Addenda, i, part ii, 1462; Cal. Pat. Rolls, Edward VI , iv, 36; Acts Privy Council, 1580-1 , 289; P.R.O., Court of Requests Procs., bundle iv, no. 258; bundle vi, no 210 .)

2 CONC 
Poems by William Cynwal and Si├ā┬┤n Brwynog refer to the prowess of Rhys Griffith (d. 1580 ) in the Irish wars , while Si├ā┬┤n Tudur implies that he had spent much of his earlier life in London . ( M
2 CONC ostyn MSS. 1, 159 ; Ll├ā┬¬n Cymru , ii, 88-9.) He m. (1) c. 1526 , Margaret , daughter of Morris ap John of Clenennau (see under Maurice and Owen of Clenennau ); by this marriage there were five sons 
2 CONC and two daughters. (2) c. 1551 , Jane , daughter of Dafydd ap William ap Griffith of Cochwillan . (3) c. 1566 , Catherine , daughter of Piers Mostyn of Talacre (see under Mostyn of Talacre ); by this 
2 CONC marriage there were two sons, Piers and William ( Griffith , Pedigrees , 185 is inaccurate on these marriages; for the second marriage, see Penrhyn MSS. 58-61 .) He was knighted at the coronation of E
2 CONC dward VI ( 1547 ) and on the accession of Mary was recommended by Nicholas Heath , archbishop of York and president of Wales , as a suitable member of parliament for Caernarvonshire . He was not elect
2 CONC ed, but was Member of Parliament for the borough of Caernarvon in 1555 and high sheriff of Caernarvonshire in 1566-7 . ( Cal. Wynn Papers , 19; Williams , Parl. Hist. Wales , 65; Breeze , Kalendars , 
2 CONC 52.) He d. 30 July 1580 ( Penrhyn MSS: 78-82 ) and was succeeded by Pirs Griffith , his eldest son by the third marriage. During his lifetime the estate passed by purchase into the possession of John 
2 CONC Williams ( 1582 - 1650 ) of the kindred house of Williams of Cochwillan ( see Williams family of Cochwillan ).
