Biography
The heir to extensive estates in Anglesey, Caernarvonshire and Cheshire, Bulkeley increased 
4 CONC his familyŌĆÖs standing in Anglesey and was instrumental in obtaining a charter of incorporation for Beaumaris in 1562. At the 1570 musters his was the highest assessment in the island. He represented
4 CONC  the county in Parliament on four occasions, and in 1571 he was a member of the committee on navigation (8 May).4

Although the family had profited from the dissolution of the monasteries, and a relat
4 CONC ive was the first protestant bishop of Bangor, a Catholic claim of 1574 that ŌĆśall the Bulkeleys are CatholicŌĆÖ is supported by Sir RichardŌĆÖs connexions. One of his aunts was the last abbess of Go
4 CONC dstow, and another married Sir William NorrisŌĆĀ of Speke. Bulkeley was taken ill early in 1572, and died 7 Sept. According to his heir he was poisoned by his second wife, whom the court of arches fou
4 CONC nd had been committing adultery with one William Kenrick who ŌĆśdid use to walk under the said Agnes her window in the night time, play upon an instrument and make love to her when Sir Richard was fro
4 CONC m home in the ParliamentŌĆÖ. Poison was found in a chest in her room, under a pair of velvet slippers, but a Beaumaris jury acquitted her of murder.5

