1 TITL Chronicling America: Historic American Newspapers, 1791-1963
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT Newspapers are fantastic sources of genealogical and family history information. Birth, marriage, and death announcements, and obituaries, are commonly used items for genealogy. However, ancestors may
2 CONC  also be mentioned in articles reporting on local news and events (i.e. social, community, school, sport, or business related events).
1 _TYPE Collection
1 _MEDI 10449
0 @S500166@ SOUR
1 _UPD 8 AUG 2024 15:30:02 GMT -0500 
1 TITL South Carolina Newspapers, 1787-2009
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT Before vital records were recorded by city, county, or state governments, local newspapers often published articles listing or detailing these events. Obituaries contain vital and biographical informa
2 CONC tion on the decedent but also on his or her family and relatives.
2 CONC Society pages began as a way to entice readers with gossip and news about the wealthy and famous but soon evolved to cover the goings-on of ŌĆ£averageŌĆØ citizens. An incredible array of information c
2 CONC an be discovered in these society pages or sections from seemingly mundane notices and reports on events such as parties, job changes, hospital stays, and social visits by friends or relatives. These 
2 CONC pages are a source of historical events that are unlikely to exist in any other record.
2 CONC Coverage and completeness in this collection varies by title.
1 _TYPE Collection
1 _MEDI 10623
0 @S500167@ SOUR
1 _UPD 8 AUG 2024 15:30:11 GMT -0500 
1 TITL United States Newspapers from OldNews.comŌäó
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT The history of a community can be explored in great detail through stories of local interest, they contain records of notable activities and events, often providing more information about any persons 
2 CONC involved, as well as context of times in which your ancestor may have lived. Images for these newspapers have been made available on <a id="" href="https://www.oldnews.com/en" class="green" target="_b
2 CONC lank" rel="noopener">OldNews.com</a>.
1 _TYPE Collection
1 _MEDI 11024
0 @S500168@ SOUR
1 _UPD 8 AUG 2024 15:31:51 GMT -0500 
1 TITL 1860 United States Federal Census
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT Federal census takers were asked to record information about every person who was in each household on the census day. A census taker might have visited a house on a later date, but the information he
2 CONC  collected was supposed to be about the people who were in the house on the census day. The basic census enumeration unit was the county. Each county was divided into enumeration districts, one for ea
2 CONC ch enumerator. The completed forms were sent to the Commerce Department's Census Office in Washington, D.C.
2 CONC Federal censuses are usually reliable, depending on the knowledge of the informant and the care of the census enumerator. Information may have been given to a census taker by any member of the family 
2 CONC or by a neighbor. Some information may have been incorrect or deliberately falsified.
1 _TYPE Collection
1 _MEDI 10127
0 @S500169@ SOUR
1 _UPD 8 AUG 2024 15:36:05 GMT -0500 
